1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,600
 22 hours a day, like how many hours?

2
00:00:01,600 --> 00:00:05,500
 I was working the answer, 70s a week, sleeping in the factory.

3
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:08,000
 I worked every time, I worked in the paint shop,

4
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,800
 General Assembly, Body Shop.

5
00:00:09,800 --> 00:00:12,600
 You ever worry about yourself imploding like it's just too much?

6
00:00:12,600 --> 00:00:13,600
 Yeah, absolutely.

7
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,100
 No one should.

8
00:00:16,100 --> 00:00:19,900
 Put the spending hours into work.

9
00:00:19,900 --> 00:00:22,200
 This is not good.

10
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:23,500
 And people should not work this hard.

11
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:25,300
 I'm not, they should not do this.

12
00:00:25,300 --> 00:00:27,700
 This is very painful.

13
00:00:27,700 --> 00:00:29,400
 Painful in what sense?

14
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:33,000
 It hurts my brain and my heart.

15
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:37,000
 So it's, this is not recommended for anyone.

16
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:39,200
 I just did it because if I didn't do it,

17
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:42,700
 then it has a good chance as I would die.

18
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:45,400
 I don't think you'd necessarily want to be me.

19
00:00:45,400 --> 00:00:48,400
 It's very hard to turn it off all the time.

20
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:49,900
 It doesn't stop.

21
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:52,900
 When I was young, I didn't really know what I was going to do.

22
00:00:52,900 --> 00:00:54,200
 When I got older.

23
00:00:54,200 --> 00:00:57,000
 I think when I was, I don't know if I was six or something.

24
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,200
 I thought I was insane.

25
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:00,200
 Because it was clear that other people

26
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:04,200
 did not, their mind wasn't exploding with ideas.

27
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:06,600
 It was just strange.

28
00:01:06,600 --> 00:01:10,000
 It was like, hmm, and strange.

29
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,400
 Eventually, I thought that the idea of inventing things

30
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:13,800
 would be really cool.

31
00:01:13,800 --> 00:01:16,000
 The reason I thought that was because I read a quote

32
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,400
 from Odyssey Clark, which said that,

33
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:21,400
 "Esfficently advanced technology is indistinguishable

34
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:22,700
 from magic."

35
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:24,200
 And that's really true.

36
00:01:24,200 --> 00:01:27,800
 If you go back, say, 300 years, the things that we take

37
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:32,600
 for granted today would be burned at the stake for.

38
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:36,100
 Being able to fly, that's crazy.

39
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:38,200
 Being able to see over long distances,

40
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:40,200
 being able to communicate this and stuff

41
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:44,200
 that really would be considered magic in time has passed.

42
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:46,400
 If I can do some of those things,

43
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:48,200
 basically, if I can advance technology,

44
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,400
 that's like magic, and that would be really cool.

45
00:01:50,400 --> 00:01:52,000
 Well, you're a little naive when you thought

46
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,800
 I can easily build an electric car and a rocket.

47
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:59,200
 I didn't think it would be easy.

48
00:01:59,200 --> 00:02:02,700
 Like I said, I thought they would probably fail.

49
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:06,200
 But creating a company is almost like having a child.

50
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:11,500
 So it's sort of like, how do you say your child should not have food?

51
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:15,800
 So once you have the company, you have to feed it and nurse it,

52
00:02:15,800 --> 00:02:20,200
 and take care of it, even if it ruins you.

53
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:25,200
 Yeah.

54
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:31,200
 But there were some tough times in the end of 2008.

55
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:35,200
 How did you get through that period of crisis?

56
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:37,200
 Yeah.

57
00:02:37,200 --> 00:02:40,200
 2000, and we just break for a second.

58
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:41,200
 Sure, sure, sure.

59
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:45,200
 You want to wait a little while.

60
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:47,200
 Sure, but what is worth it?

61
00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:49,200
 Sure, but what is worth it?

62
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:54,200
 One of the most difficult choices I have ever faced in life was in 2008.

63
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:58,200
 I think I had maybe $30 million left, $30 or $40 million left in 2008.

64
00:02:58,200 --> 00:02:59,200
 I had two choices.

65
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:05,200
 I could put it all into one company, and then the other company would definitely die,

66
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:07,200
 or split it between the two companies.

67
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:11,200
 And if I split up between the two companies, then both went down.

68
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:15,200
 And where you put your blood sweat and tears into creating something,

69
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:17,200
 building something, it's like a child.

70
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:22,200
 And so it's like, which one am I going to let one stop to death?

71
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:24,200
 I couldn't bring myself to do it, so I put my--

72
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:27,200
 I just put 20 between two.

73
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:30,200
 I want you to really think about that working through.

74
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:33,200
 You know, with Tesla, we're like trying to make things that people love.

75
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,200
 How do I-- how do things keep by that?

76
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:37,200
 You really love that.

77
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:39,200
 Really give you joy.

78
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:40,200
 So rare.

79
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:41,200
 So rare.

80
00:03:41,200 --> 00:03:43,200
 I wish there were more things.

81
00:03:43,200 --> 00:03:44,200
 That's what we're trying to do.

82
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:47,200
 Just make things that somebody loves.

83
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:48,200
 Yes.

84
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:52,200
 Doing something useful for other people that I like doing.

85
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:58,200
 Generally, starting a business, I'd say number one is have a high-paying threshold.

86
00:03:58,200 --> 00:04:02,200
 That's-- there's a friend of mine who's got a good saying,

87
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:05,200
 which is that starting a company is like eating glass and staring into the abyss.

88
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:08,200
 That's generally what happens, because when you first start a company,

89
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:11,200
 there's lots of optimism, and things of things are great.

90
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:14,200
 So happiness at first is high.

91
00:04:14,200 --> 00:04:16,200
 Then you encounter all sorts of issues.

92
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:18,200
 And happiness will steadily decline.

93
00:04:18,200 --> 00:04:21,200
 And then you'll go through a whole world of hurt.

94
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:25,200
 That's-- and then eventually, if you succeed,

95
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:30,200
 and in most cases, you will not succeed, and Tesla almost succeed,

96
00:04:30,200 --> 00:04:34,200
 and very close to go, then if you succeed, then after a long time,

97
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:37,200
 you will finally get back to happiness.

98
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:42,200
 And I want to know, what is the one thing that is surprised you about your life?

99
00:04:42,200 --> 00:04:45,200
 Well, I certainly-- I'm surprised by the whole thing, honestly.

100
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:47,200
 I certainly didn't expect to be-- to be--

101
00:04:47,200 --> 00:04:50,200
 to be one of these things to happen, honestly.

102
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:53,200
 In fact, the only reason I started a company back in '95,

103
00:04:53,200 --> 00:04:55,200
 an era company was because I couldn't get it--

104
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:57,200
 there were only a few internet companies,

105
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:00,200
 and I couldn't get a job at any of them.

106
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:03,200
 I tried to get a job at Netscape,

107
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:07,200
 and Santa Maria and I tried hanging out in the lobby,

108
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:09,200
 but I was too shy to talk to anyone.

109
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:13,200
 And I was like, OK, well, I guess I'll have to start a company

110
00:05:13,200 --> 00:05:15,200
 because I can't get a job anywhere.

111
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:17,200
 Really, really liking what you do.

112
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:21,200
 Whatever area that you get into, given that, you know,

113
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:25,200
 even if you're the best, the best, there's always a chance of failure.

114
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:28,200
 So I think it's important that you really like whatever you're doing.

115
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:31,200
 If you don't like it, life is too short.

116
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:33,200
 If you like what you're doing, you think about it,

117
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:35,200
 even when you're not working.

118
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:37,200
 It's something that your mind is drawn to.

119
00:05:37,200 --> 00:05:41,200
 And if you don't like it, you just really can't make a work, I think.

120
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:43,200
 Well, you want to do, particularly if you're starting a company,

121
00:05:43,200 --> 00:05:45,200
 you need to work super hard.

122
00:05:45,200 --> 00:05:47,200
 So what does super hard mean?

123
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:50,200
 When my brother and I were starting our first company,

124
00:05:50,200 --> 00:05:51,200
 I didn't have any money.

125
00:05:51,200 --> 00:05:52,200
 In fact, I had negative money.

126
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:54,200
 I had huge student debts.

127
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:57,200
 In fact, I couldn't afford a place to stay and an office.

128
00:05:57,200 --> 00:05:59,200
 So instead of getting an apartment,

129
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:03,200
 we just rented a small office and we slept on the couch.

130
00:06:03,200 --> 00:06:06,200
 And we shared it with the YMCA.

131
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:09,200
 And there was an ISP on the floor below us.

132
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:11,200
 Just a little tiny ISP.

133
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:13,200
 And we drilled a hole through the floor

134
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:15,200
 and connected a normal room cable.

135
00:06:15,200 --> 00:06:18,200
 That gave us our internet connectivity for like 100 bucks a month.

136
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:21,200
 And we're so hot up, we had just one computer.

137
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:23,200
 So the website was up during the day

138
00:06:23,200 --> 00:06:25,200
 and I was coding at night.

139
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:27,200
 Seven days a week, all the time.

140
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:29,200
 And I briefly had a girlfriend in that period.

141
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:31,200
 And in order to be with me,

142
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:33,200
 she had to sleep in the office.

143
00:06:33,200 --> 00:06:36,200
 So we're quite like, I mean, every waking hour.

144
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:38,200
 That's the thing I would say particularly

145
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:40,200
 if you're starting a company.

146
00:06:40,200 --> 00:06:42,200
 It's very important to actively seek out

147
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:45,200
 and listen very carefully to negative feedback.

148
00:06:45,200 --> 00:06:48,200
 And this is something that people tend to avoid

149
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:52,200
 because it's painful when friends get a product.

150
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:54,200
 I said, look, don't tell me what you like.

151
00:06:54,200 --> 00:06:55,200
 Tell me what you don't like.

152
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:57,200
 Otherwise, your friend is not going to tell you what it doesn't like.

153
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:00,200
 Right. This is going to say, oh, I love this and that.

154
00:07:00,200 --> 00:07:03,200
 And then leave out the, this is the stuff I don't like list.

155
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:05,200
 And sometimes even your enemies give you good negative feedback.

156
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:08,200
 So I actually went to, I went to Russia three times

157
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:11,200
 to look at buying a refurbished ICVM.

158
00:07:11,200 --> 00:07:14,200
 I can tell you it was very weird going there in 2000,

159
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:18,200
 late 2001, 2002, going to the Russian rocket forces

160
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:21,200
 and saying, I'd like to buy two of your biggest rockets.

161
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:23,200
 They thought I was crazy, but I did have money.

162
00:07:23,200 --> 00:07:26,200
 So that was, that was okay.

163
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:30,200
 One good friend of mine collected a whole series of videos

164
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:33,200
 of rockets blowing up and made me watch those.

165
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:35,200
 He just didn't want me to lose all my money.

166
00:07:35,200 --> 00:07:38,200
 For SpaceX, the first three launches failed.

167
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:41,200
 We're just barely able to scrape together enough

168
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:44,200
 parts and money to do the fourth launch.

169
00:07:44,200 --> 00:07:47,200
 That fourth launch had failed. We would have been dead.

170
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:50,200
 I tried very hard to get the right expertise

171
00:07:50,200 --> 00:07:54,200
 in for SpaceX. I tried hard to find a great

172
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:56,200
 chief engineer for the rocket,

173
00:07:56,200 --> 00:07:58,200
 but the good chief engineers wouldn't join.

174
00:07:58,200 --> 00:08:00,200
 And the bad ones, well there was no point in hiring you.

175
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:03,200
 So I ended up being chief engineer of the rocket.

176
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:05,200
 So if I could have found somebody better

177
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:08,200
 than we would have maybe had less than three failures.

178
00:08:08,200 --> 00:08:11,200
 When you had that third failure in a row,

179
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:14,200
 did you think I need to pack this thing?

180
00:08:14,200 --> 00:08:17,200
 Never. Why not?

181
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:19,200
 I don't ever give up.

182
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:24,200
 I mean, I'd have to be dead or proving to have passed it.

183
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:28,200
 You know there are American heroes who don't like this idea.

184
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:30,200
 Neil Armstrong, Gene Cernan,

185
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:34,200
 have both testified against commercial spaceflight

186
00:08:34,200 --> 00:08:36,200
 in the way that you're developing it.

187
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:39,200
 And I wonder what you think of that.

188
00:08:39,200 --> 00:08:43,200
 I was very sad to see that, because those guys are...

189
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:45,200
 Yeah.

190
00:08:45,200 --> 00:08:48,200
 You know, those guys are heroes of mine, so it's really tough.

191
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:50,200
 No, I wish they would come and visit

192
00:08:50,200 --> 00:08:53,200
 and see the hardware I was doing here.

193
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:56,200
 And I think that would change their mind.

194
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:58,200
 They inspired you to do this, didn't they?

195
00:08:58,200 --> 00:09:01,200
 Yes.

196
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:05,200
 And to see them casting stones in your direction.

197
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:09,200
 It's difficult.

198
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:13,200
 Did you expect them to cheer you on?

199
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:15,200
 So they're hoping you would.

200
00:09:15,200 --> 00:09:20,200
 The critics say you can't do this. Your answer to them is we've done it.

